It&rsquo;s not only the Chief Executive&rsquo;s popularity that&rsquo;s constantly slipping in the polls, it&rsquo;s also the level of satisfaction with his Policy Address. This is his third and indeed the longest since the handover, but only 30% of participants in one poll thought that quantity equaled quality.&nbsp;In part two of today&rsquo;s show, we&rsquo;re looking at Mr Leung&rsquo;s plans to strengthen students&rsquo; affection for the motherland, and the difference between rule of law and rule by law.&nbsp;But first, housing and high property prices. Is there really any plan to improve the situation? This year&rsquo;s Policy Address is increasing love for the Motherland, if not the ruling party. Measures he announced include renewing the content of the Chinese History and World History curriculum, increased subsidies for mainland exchange programmes, and the introduction of a pilot &ldquo;sister schools&rdquo; scheme with mainland schools.&nbsp;

How frustrating it can be for a government when courts insist on rule OF law instead of rule BY law. While the Chief Executive stressed adherence to the law in his Address this week, speeches at the opening of the Legal Year on Monday suggested that HIS version of what law should be may not be quite how judges and practicing lawyers see things.&nbsp;  

2015-01-09


On Wednesday Chief Secretary Carrie Lam announced the second part of the consultationn proposed political reforms, that the democrats have already vowed to veto.&nbsp;What chance is there that the consultation exercise is going to be another way of telling Beijing exactly what it wants to hear?&nbsp;With us in the studio are Basic Law Committee member Albert Chen and legislator Ronny Tong to talk about the blank vote proposal.

The reckoning has begun. The more than two month occupation of some of Hong Kong&rsquo;s thoroughfares ended in December.&nbsp;Now the police are proceeding with prosecutions of those they believe to be largely responsible for the protests. They are said to have a list of nearly 1,500 people subject to investigation. Some thirty received notification this week. Among those facing prosecution are students, some of whom are legally minors.&nbsp;

THE PULSE ON 3/4/2015
After months of uncertainty and rumour, after government decisions that have baffled many, there&rsquo;s a dramatic turn in the story of the
beleaguered&nbsp;ATV. After a special Executive Council meeting on Wednesday afternoon, the government announced it was not renewing the station&rsquo;s free-to-air license.&nbsp;With us in the studio are Ip Ka-po,&nbsp;Executive Director of ATV, and John Medeiros, Chief Policy Officer ofCASBAA.


Early on Thursday morning, another cross was taken off the roof of another church in Ningbo. This is the latest move in the crackdown on Christianity and its churches in China's Zhejiang province, home to the country&rsquo;s most Christian city, Wenzhou.
Christianity arrived in China as far back as the Tang dynasty, and &ndash; worryingly for the Chinese Communist Party, which doesn&rsquo;t countenance any alternatives to its authority &ndash; it&rsquo;s getting ever more popular. It doesn&rsquo;t help that Christian values are also regarded as a pernicious &ldquo;foreign influence&rdquo;.To get a better understanding of what&rsquo;s going on, our producer Jerran Lin recently visited Wenzhou, sometimes called &ldquo;the Jerusalem of China&rdquo;, where Christians told her they are facing the worst suppression in decades.


DUE TO PROGRAMME CHANGE, THE PULSE ON 27/3/2015 WAS PREEMPTED. HERE IS THE ARCHIVE OF THAT EPISODE.&nbsp;





On Monday Singapore&rsquo;s prime minister Lee Hsien Loong announced the death of his father Lee Kuan Yew, Singapore&rsquo;s founding prime minister, and the man who led the country for 31 years.The city state has begun seven days of national mourning, but there are also some people reassessing his legacy.&nbsp;With us in the studio are Stephan Ortmann of the Asian &amp; International Studies Department at City University and the former editor of&nbsp;the Far Eastern Economic Review Philip Bowring.&nbsp;


What does Hong Kong need to boost innovation and technology? Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying believes we absolutely need an Innovation and Technology Bureau. Last year, the government asked legislators for funds to set it up but this request was blocked, at least for now, by a pan-democrat filibuster at the Finance Committee.

They say, we already have a HK$13 billion Cyberport and a 22-hectare Science Park, with a third phase that alone will cost HK$4.9 billion. Meanwhile the jury is still out on how much these organisations have boosted innovation. The new bureau&rsquo;s sceptics also say the Mr Leung has no clear vision for it, and that his broader plan, which also includes a culture bureau and more political appointees, is mostly about creating new political posts for his allies. Mr Leung will come&nbsp; back to Legco again next month to try and get the funds he needs for this bueau.&nbsp;

The Pearl River Delta has for years been the production base for Hong Kong manufacturers.&nbsp;But China&rsquo;s economy has changed.&nbsp;No longer is labour cheap, nor is it in abundant supply for factory work.&nbsp;For the manufacturers, relocation of their production plants is the answer.
&nbsp;
Producer: Clara Li

Political magazines have never enjoyed any significant readership in Hong Kong.&nbsp;But they have been given a new lease of life in recent years.&nbsp;Their contents are almost always exposes of secrets of the Communist regime and visitors from the mainland find them most intriguing.
&nbsp;
Producer: Gillian Yau

Hong Kong as a community is not 100% homogenous.&nbsp;There are about 100,000 people of various ethnicities.&nbsp;Despite being permanent residents, most of them seem unable to get an SAR passport.
&nbsp;
Producer: &nbsp;Clara Li

TVB and ATV are the two stations providing free television in Hong Kong.&nbsp;The former takes in 95 per cent of the money from advertisers.&nbsp;The latter keeps operating in the red.&nbsp;No one in the public seems happy with either one&rsquo;s programme quality.&nbsp;Should there be a third station?&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Producer: &nbsp;Phoebe Chan

There has been an influx of Chinese private-owned companies, generally referred to private enterprises, to be listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange.&nbsp;Not all of them, however, are doing business in a legitimate fashion.
&nbsp;
Producer: Choy Yuk-ling

The powers that be in Beijing have announced a renewed resolve in tackling corruption.&nbsp;While it is too early to see results, rural communities are showing impatience.&nbsp;They are saying they can only rely on themselves.
&nbsp;
Producer: Eric Poon

Housing is a perennial problem in Hong Kong.&nbsp;With supply falling way short of demand, property is so expensive it is hard for the common man or woman to find a decent roof over their heads. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Producer: Flora Yeung

Controversy has once again erupted in Hong Kong over the Executive Council&rsquo;s decision not to grant Hong Kong Television Network a broadcasting licence.&nbsp;There is a demand to know how the decision was arrived at and there is the question: Who really is the loser?&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Producer: Paul Lee, Dora Choi &amp; Fanny Kwan

